            <h2>About Me</h2>
            <p class="lead">
              I’m a PhD candidate in Geophysics at MIT Department of Earth, Atmospheric, and Planetary Sciences studying how fault zones and
              volcanoes evolve through time. 
              I develop time-lapse seismo-geodetic monitoring techniques—including receiver function methods to track changes in seismic velocity and anisotropy throughout the crust. 
              I've studied Mount St. Helens and the 2019 Ridgecrest sequence. 
              In parallel, I study tidal asteroseismology, linking planet-driven stellar oscillations to orbital evolution. 
              I also design field-ready instrumentation and low-power electronics for dense, long-duration deployments.
            </p>

